00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:31.670
- My name's Dylan Penningroth,

00:00:31.670 --> 00:00:34.480
I'm a Professor of Law and
History here at Berkeley,

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:38.420
and I'm chair of the Jefferson
Memorial Lectures Committee.

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:40.590
Just a little bit of background
about these lectures,

00:00:40.590 --> 00:00:43.570
they were established way
back in 1980, excuse me,

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:47.670
1944, through a bequest
from Elizabeth Bonestell

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:50.683
and her husband Cutler L.
Bonestell of San Francisco,

00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:55.270
and the Bonestells cared
deeply about history,

00:00:55.270 --> 00:00:58.600
and they hoped that these
lectures would encourage students,

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:01.090
faculty, scholars, and area residents

00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:03.850
to study the legacy of Thomas Jefferson,

00:01:03.850 --> 00:01:08.030
and to explore values inherent
to American democracy.

00:01:08.030 --> 00:01:11.710
And past lecturers, who have
included Annette Gordon-Reed,

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:15.630
Senator Alan Simpson,
Senator Elizabeth Warren,

00:01:15.630 --> 00:01:19.250
Archibald Cox, and most
recently, George Packer,

00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:20.890
have delivered Jefferson Lectures

00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:24.500
on early American history,
about Jefferson himself,

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:26.470
and on American institutions and policies

00:01:26.470 --> 00:01:29.620
in politics, economics,
education, and law.

00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:31.810
Now, before I go any further,

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:36.810
I have to say that any event
like this is a group effort,

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:40.420
as any of you who have
organized one will know,

00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:43.400
and the committee, which
includes Mark Brilliant,

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:46.530
Paul Pearson, Wendy Silver, Karen Tawny,

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:50.650
Christopher Tomlins, and I join me

00:01:50.650 --> 00:01:53.980
in thanking Whitney
Mellow, Sevala Travinsky,

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:57.480
and especially Ellen Gobler,
who you just saw up here,

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:01.293
for their deft and tactful
handling of all the logistics.

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:05.630
So we're pleased on behalf
of the Graduate Division

00:02:05.630 --> 00:02:06.980
to present this year's speaker

00:02:06.980 --> 00:02:10.763
in the Jefferson Memorial
Lecture Series, David Cole.

00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:13.960
So in July, 2016,

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.980
David Cole was named
National Legal Director

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:20.660
of the American Civil Liberties
Union, our country's largest

00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:23.853
and oldest civil liberties organization.

00:02:24.690 --> 00:02:26.880
So in July, 2016, you may remember,

00:02:26.880 --> 00:02:31.880
The New York Times gave
Hillary Clinton a 74% chance

00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:36.940
of becoming president, it
looked like things were going

00:02:36.940 --> 00:02:41.940
to be, well, maybe not all
right, but at least aight.

00:02:42.277 --> 00:02:43.510
(audience laughs)

00:02:43.510 --> 00:02:44.882
Right?

00:02:44.882 --> 00:02:46.560
(audience murmurs)

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:49.420
We all know what happened next, and thanks

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:54.420
to Robert Mueller, we're slowly
finding out how it happened,

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:56.700
now, David Cole has been at the forefront

00:02:56.700 --> 00:03:00.620
of those who are fighting the
consequences of what happened.

00:03:00.620 --> 00:03:02.150
Since that fateful November,

00:03:02.150 --> 00:03:05.980
this already busy man
has become even busier,

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:09.240
as National Legal Director, he oversees

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:14.240
about 1,400 civil liberties
lawsuits, and manages over,

00:03:15.204 --> 00:03:19.010
excuse me, 300 staff
attorneys at ACLU headquarters

00:03:19.010 --> 00:03:22.670
in New York, and affiliate
offices in all 50 states,

00:03:22.670 --> 00:03:25.670
Puerto Rico, and Washington, DC.

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:27.430
There has never been a better time

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:31.747
to become what the first
George Bush once scorned,

00:03:31.747 --> 00:03:35.357
"a card carrying member of the ACLU."

00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:39.580
Now, Cole was law clerk
to Judge Arlin Adams

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:42.270
of the Third Circuit Court of Appeals,

00:03:42.270 --> 00:03:43.310
he was a staff attorney

00:03:43.310 --> 00:03:44.780
at the Center for Constitutional Rights,

00:03:44.780 --> 00:03:46.630
and he taught constitutional law

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:48.710
and criminal justice at Georgetown,

00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:51.190
as the Honorable George
J. Mitchell Professor

00:03:51.190 --> 00:03:52.940
in Law and Public Policy.

00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:56.300
He's argued a number of
major civil liberties cases,

00:03:56.300 --> 00:03:59.170
including Texas versus Johnson,

00:03:59.170 --> 00:04:02.950
which struck down state laws
banning flag desecration,

00:04:02.950 --> 00:04:05.230
National Endowment for
the Arts versus Finley,

00:04:05.230 --> 00:04:09.003
which contested content
restrictions on NEA funding,

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:12.570
and Holder versus
Humanitarian Law Project,

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:15.300
which challenged the
legality of a provision

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:19.130
in the USA Patriot Act barring,
quote, "material support,"

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:22.740
end quote, to foreign
terrorist organizations.

00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:26.410
In December, 2017, he
argued Masterpiece Cake Shop

00:04:26.410 --> 00:04:29.590
versus Colorado Civil Rights Commission,

00:04:29.590 --> 00:04:33.450
in which the rights of free
exercise, or free expression,

00:04:33.450 --> 00:04:36.210
and the right in public accommodations

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:38.410
to protection against bias based

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:42.200
on sexual orientation
come together in conflict,

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:45.980
or what the legal historian
Rebecca J. Scott has called,

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:50.907
in another context, "public
rights, or the equal dignity

00:04:50.907 --> 00:04:54.797
"of citizens in the public
sphere, these are the stakes."

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.100
Cole has written or edited 10 books,

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:01.400
he's Legal Affairs
Correspondent for The Nation,

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:04.290
and a regular commentator
on National Public Radio.

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:06.410
He's received two honorary degrees,

00:05:06.410 --> 00:05:08.730
and many awards for his civil liberties

00:05:08.730 --> 00:05:12.450
and human rights work, including, in 2013,

00:05:12.450 --> 00:05:16.930
the first Norman Dorsen
Presidential Prize from the ACLU,

00:05:16.930 --> 00:05:19.870
awarded to an academic
for lifetime commitment

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:21.143
to civil liberties.

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:25.697
For his Jefferson
Lecture, Cole asks, quote,

00:05:25.697 --> 00:05:27.657
"What does the first year of fighting

00:05:27.657 --> 00:05:31.343
"for liberty tell us
about constitutional law,

00:05:31.343 --> 00:05:33.027
"and the future of civil liberties

00:05:33.027 --> 00:05:35.920
"and civil rights in the United States?"

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:39.716
Please join me in welcoming
David Cole to Berkeley.

00:05:39.716 --> 00:05:42.716
(audience applauds)

00:05:53.810 --> 00:05:58.810
- Thank you so much for that
very lovely introduction,

00:06:01.437 --> 00:06:03.820
I, when I get an introduction like that,

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:07.410
I'm often, it often calls to
mind what Justice Brennan used

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:12.410
to say, when he got similar
over-the-top introductions,

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:16.287
he would say, you know, "I
wish my parents had been here

00:06:16.287 --> 00:06:20.577
"to hear it, my father
would have been proud,

00:06:20.577 --> 00:06:22.615
"and my mother would have believed it."

00:06:22.615 --> 00:06:24.330
(audience laughs)

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:26.960
So, and I am delighted

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:30.560
to be giving the Thomas
Jefferson lecture, I was,

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:35.560
earlier today, interviewed
for a video presentation,

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:38.190
and the, here at Berkeley,

00:06:38.190 --> 00:06:41.740
and the person who was
doing the taping referred

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:46.047
to me as Mr. Jefferson, so I
thought that was interesting.

00:06:46.047 --> 00:06:48.340
(audience laughs)

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:52.840
But I will, I'll talk mostly
about the last year, and more

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:56.700
about what Donald Trump can
teach us about civil liberties

00:06:56.700 --> 00:07:00.823
than what Thomas Jefferson can teach us.

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:03.760
My principal

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:09.210
message here is that
while this is a dark time,

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:12.050
and there's no question
that it is a dark time

00:07:12.050 --> 00:07:15.640
in our, in our country,
for a variety of reasons,

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:20.640
and for a variety of
segments of our population,

00:07:20.670 --> 00:07:24.603
it is also a time of opportunity.

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:28.720
And I think a time of,

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.310
of hope,

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:32.820
and secondly,

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:35.780
that we will determine

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:40.340
how this time is ultimately viewed

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:41.910
in history,

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:44.650
and if we respond

00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:48.290
by exercising our civil liberties,

00:07:48.290 --> 00:07:53.290
we can, I think, transform
what is a very dark time

00:07:53.950 --> 00:07:56.400
into essentially a catalyst

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:00.233
for a renewed progressive movement.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:04.820
So it's easy, I think, to convince people

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:06.060
that these are dark times,

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:11.060
and I'm sure you've heard many
talks, and many, you know,

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:13.960
guests on talk shows talk
about how dark it is,

00:08:13.960 --> 00:08:18.870
but I really want to look at
the other side of the coin,

00:08:18.870 --> 00:08:22.940
and that is where opportunity lies.

00:08:22.940 --> 00:08:24.700
But first, in terms of, you know,

00:08:24.700 --> 00:08:27.810
how things have changed, Dylan mentioned

00:08:27.810 --> 00:08:31.647
that I was hired in July, 2016,

00:08:31.647 --> 00:08:35.990
and I was hired, I was
recruited for the job

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:38.910
by the Executive Director of the ACLU,

00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:41.250
Anthony Romero, who came
down to Washington, DC,

00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:44.967
where I was teaching at
Georgetown, and he said,

00:08:44.967 --> 00:08:48.107
"David, you know, I've got
an offer you can't refuse.

00:08:48.107 --> 00:08:52.117
"You have been teaching
constitutional law,

00:08:52.117 --> 00:08:55.647
"practicing constitutional
law for 30 something years

00:08:55.647 --> 00:08:59.737
"under a conservative
majority Supreme Court.

00:08:59.737 --> 00:09:02.317
"Just think what it would be like

00:09:02.317 --> 00:09:05.027
"to run the ACLU's legal docket,

00:09:05.027 --> 00:09:07.667
"and especially it's Supreme Court work

00:09:07.667 --> 00:09:11.380
"under a liberal majority Supreme Court."

00:09:11.380 --> 00:09:13.680
And, of course, The New
York Times may have had it

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:16.050
at 74%, that Hillary Clinton would win,

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:18.530
I had it at 100%, that
Hillary Clinton would win,

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:22.607
and I think most of the
people I knew had it at 100%,

00:09:22.607 --> 00:09:27.240
and so she would, of
course, name the successor

00:09:27.240 --> 00:09:30.640
to Justice Scalia, and we would have,

00:09:30.640 --> 00:09:32.690
for the first time in four decades,

00:09:32.690 --> 00:09:35.440
a liberal majority Supreme Court.

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:38.770
So I, of course, I signed
on the bottom line,

00:09:38.770 --> 00:09:43.770
I went to law school back in the 1980s,

00:09:43.780 --> 00:09:48.780
and my professors were
all people who had come up

00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:53.090
and become lawyers and law professors

00:09:53.090 --> 00:09:58.090
in the civil rights movement
under the watchful eye

00:09:58.420 --> 00:10:01.770
of the Warren Court, the
Supreme Court under the tenure

00:10:01.770 --> 00:10:05.330
of Earl Warren, the most
progressive Supreme Court

00:10:05.330 --> 00:10:09.070
in the history of this
country, and that's the vision

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:11.460
of constitutional law that they taught me.

00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:13.500
And then I graduated, and went out,

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:16.780
and practiced under a conservative
majority Supreme Court

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:20.450
for three plus decades, so
I thought this was a great,

00:10:20.450 --> 00:10:23.070
a great opportunity, I
signed on the bottom line,

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:24.930
I didn't put in a conditional what-if,

00:10:24.930 --> 00:10:27.960
because there was no what if, right?

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:30.300
And I immediately, I
didn't start immediately,

00:10:30.300 --> 00:10:32.640
because I was finishing up
my teaching at Georgetown,

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:37.320
but I, you know, immediately
tasked the ACLU lawyers

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:42.320
to write memos on how we could
advance constitutional law

00:10:42.680 --> 00:10:44.800
under this liberal Supreme Court

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:48.510
that we were sure to be operating under,

00:10:48.510 --> 00:10:51.670
and those are really interesting memos.

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:53.383
They're now in the wastebasket.

00:10:54.963 --> 00:10:59.207
And obviously, everything
changed on November 8th.

00:11:01.216 --> 00:11:05.403
The, I still hadn't started
to work for the ACLU, but the,

00:11:09.130 --> 00:11:10.600
the Executive Director decided

00:11:10.600 --> 00:11:13.550
to introduce me to the national staff

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:17.610
at a national staff
meeting, which he scheduled

00:11:17.610 --> 00:11:22.500
for November 9th, the
morning after the election.

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:25.290
You can imagine that staff meeting was not

00:11:25.290 --> 00:11:29.773
about introducing me,
it was about what had,

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:35.660
what had just, what had just
transpired, and people were,

00:11:36.050 --> 00:11:37.921
you know, many of the staff were,

00:11:37.921 --> 00:11:39.540
you know, in shock, as I'm sure, you know,

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:41.620
many of your students
were, many of the people

00:11:41.620 --> 00:11:43.180
in this room, probably, were in shock

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:47.100
because no one ever
thought this could happen,

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:48.480
and everyone was very concerned

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:52.870
about what it might,
what it might portend.

00:11:52.870 --> 00:11:56.800
And it did change, in many
ways, in fundamental ways,

00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:58.850
the way that we operate,
but in other ways, no,

00:11:58.850 --> 00:12:02.003
I mean, we, we've been around since 1920.

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:05.360
We've sued Republican presidents,

00:12:05.360 --> 00:12:09.340
we've sued Democratic
presidents, we sued the Bushes,

00:12:09.340 --> 00:12:12.320
we sued Clinton, we sued Obama,

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:16.380
so in that respect, you
know, we will sue Trump.

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:19.220
We have sued Trump, that's
not that much of a change,

00:12:19.220 --> 00:12:23.230
but we went from the possibility

00:12:23.230 --> 00:12:26.110
of working on offense,
and having an inside game

00:12:26.110 --> 00:12:29.120
with a Justice Department that shared some

00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:32.340
of our most basic beliefs and values

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:36.350
to having to play a
largely defensive game,

00:12:36.350 --> 00:12:40.500
and one in which we,
we have to rely largely

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:45.500
on an outside game, rather
than an inside game.

00:12:45.640 --> 00:12:49.220
But, in many ways, it's times like this

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:53.720
when organizations like
ours are so critical,

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:57.070
and so important, and one of the reasons

00:12:57.070 --> 00:13:02.070
that I feel buoyed and hopeful
in this time is the response

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:06.500
of the citizenry to the
election of Donald Trump.

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:10.080
So Donald Trump walks
like an authoritarian,

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:12.640
he talks like an authoritarian,

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:15.940
but he doesn't rule like an authoritarian,

00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:18.410
and the reason he doesn't
rule like an authoritarian,

00:13:18.410 --> 00:13:21.580
at least thus far, is because he can't,

00:13:21.580 --> 00:13:26.230
because there's been significant
resistance from citizens,

00:13:26.230 --> 00:13:31.230
from courts, from civil
society in a variety of ways,

00:13:31.810 --> 00:13:36.100
and those checks are absolutely critical.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:38.983
So, you know, there are
many examples of the,

00:13:40.590 --> 00:13:45.010
of the response to
President Trump's election.

00:13:45.010 --> 00:13:50.010
Here, this is our first response,
"we'll see you in court,"

00:13:51.250 --> 00:13:54.740
and for a long time, this
was, this was what you saw,

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:57.330
Donald Trump's visage on the front page

00:13:57.330 --> 00:14:02.330
of the ACLU website, and
we, two days after that,

00:14:03.930 --> 00:14:07.930
that staff, that staff
meeting, on November 9th,

00:14:07.930 --> 00:14:11.180
we published in The New York Times

00:14:11.180 --> 00:14:14.060
and the Washington Post this letter

00:14:14.060 --> 00:14:17.077
to president-elect Trump,
"For nearly 100 years,

00:14:17.077 --> 00:14:20.237
"the ACLU has stood as the
nation's premier defender

00:14:20.237 --> 00:14:22.527
"of freedom and justice for all,

00:14:22.527 --> 00:14:24.447
"as you assume the
nation's highest office,

00:14:24.447 --> 00:14:27.017
"we must ask you now, as president-elect,

00:14:27.017 --> 00:14:29.357
"to reconsider and change course

00:14:29.357 --> 00:14:32.640
"on certain campaign
promises you have made."

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.500
And we then went through the
campaign promises he had made,

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:38.670
including the Muslim ban, and said,

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:43.670
if you carry these promises
through, we'll see you in court.

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:50.900
And that's what, that's
what we have, we have done,

00:14:51.450 --> 00:14:55.993
we have sued the president
over the Muslim ban,

00:14:56.851 --> 00:14:59.410
on many occasions, and I'll
come back to that in a moment.

00:14:59.410 --> 00:15:04.410
We've sued him over the
attempts to deport Dreamers,

00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:10.460
people who have, have the
protection of the, of DACA,

00:15:10.460 --> 00:15:14.390
those are the young people who
were brought here illegally

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:16.830
by their parents, and are, but at no fault

00:15:16.830 --> 00:15:18.750
of their own, and are undocumented,

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:22.360
we sued him over his Voter
Integrity Commission,

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:25.080
which was essentially designed to try to

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:30.080
create the basis for suppressing the vote.

00:15:30.686 --> 00:15:32.090
We sued him

00:15:33.090 --> 00:15:35.260
over his,

00:15:35.260 --> 00:15:37.920
his administration's policy

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:40.520
of obstructing access

00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:45.030
to young undocumented women who are

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:46.660
in federal custody

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:50.283
here, and seek an abortion.

00:15:51.230 --> 00:15:53.090
And his,

00:15:53.090 --> 00:15:57.860
his choice to head up the
Office of Refugee Resettlement,

00:15:57.860 --> 00:16:02.860
a man named Scott Lloyd, who
has no history or experience

00:16:03.920 --> 00:16:08.477
in immigration, but is an
ardent anti-choice person,

00:16:09.990 --> 00:16:14.710
has taken it upon himself
to essentially bar the door.

00:16:14.710 --> 00:16:17.120
When young women who are
detained because they're,

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:21.810
they've been, you know,
captured as undocumented here,

