00:19:37.780 --> 00:19:41.310
without a warrant,
without going to a judge.

00:19:41.310 --> 00:19:45.730
And, of course, we sued
him over the travel ban,

00:19:45.730 --> 00:19:49.380
that is also before the Supreme Court,

00:19:49.380 --> 00:19:51.810
now, for the second time this term,

00:19:51.810 --> 00:19:54.833
and will be argued in April.

00:19:55.910 --> 00:20:00.030
So, so we told them,
"We'll see you in court,"

00:20:00.030 --> 00:20:02.580
and we have indeed seen them in court,

00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:07.580
and by and large, the courts
have stood up to the president.

00:20:07.890 --> 00:20:11.580
So the courts have
enjoined the Muslim ban,

00:20:11.580 --> 00:20:14.330
repeatedly, three different versions

00:20:14.330 --> 00:20:18.310
of the Muslim ban have
been enjoined, repeatedly.

00:20:18.310 --> 00:20:22.460
The court's enjoined the
transgender military ban,

00:20:22.460 --> 00:20:27.010
the court's barred the Office
of Refugee Resettlement

00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:32.010
from keeping women from their
right to, to obtain abortion,

00:20:34.465 --> 00:20:39.465
the courts have rescinded
President Trump's rescission

00:20:40.080 --> 00:20:44.451
of DACA, the protection for the Dreamers.

00:20:44.451 --> 00:20:47.840
The courts have enjoined the policy

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:52.300
that would allow employers to
deny contraceptive coverage

00:20:52.300 --> 00:20:55.173
to their employees if they object.

00:20:57.449 --> 00:21:01.250
So, so by and large,
the courts have stood up

00:21:01.250 --> 00:21:04.273
to the president, and I
think that's, you know,

00:21:06.940 --> 00:21:10.170
as it should be, it's not as it always is,

00:21:10.170 --> 00:21:12.630
and, of course, we have not yet heard

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:15.230
from the Supreme Court on
any of these questions,

00:21:15.230 --> 00:21:18.950
and that's where the rubber
ultimately meets the road.

00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:23.950
But in a time of unified government,

00:21:24.290 --> 00:21:28.100
that is, the same party
controlling the presidency,

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:31.610
both houses of Congress, and, indeed,

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:34.083
right now, the Supreme Court,

00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:37.150
the

00:21:37.150 --> 00:21:39.750
courts, nonetheless, continue

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:43.860
to play an important
role in checking abuse.

00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:47.360
And why is that, well, one, the politics

00:21:47.360 --> 00:21:52.170
of the courts lags behind
the politics of the moment,

00:21:52.170 --> 00:21:56.100
because judges are appointed
by a particular party

00:21:56.100 --> 00:21:59.350
at a particular time, but
then they serve for life,

00:21:59.350 --> 00:22:01.913
and so the courts'

00:22:04.130 --> 00:22:07.580
outlook changes much more slowly than the,

00:22:07.580 --> 00:22:10.300
than Congress or the
president, number one.

00:22:10.300 --> 00:22:12.863
Number two, the courts are,

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:17.280
their self-definition is

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:22.280
to be independent checks
applying law to politics,

00:22:23.020 --> 00:22:26.410
and while there is obviously
reason to be skeptical

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:28.780
that they always do that,
and that it's possible

00:22:28.780 --> 00:22:30.380
to separate law from politics,

00:22:30.380 --> 00:22:35.380
it is critical to their
legitimacy as institutional actors

00:22:35.410 --> 00:22:38.430
to hold true to that ideal,

00:22:38.430 --> 00:22:41.630
and so courts do,

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:45.150
in many instances, hold
true to that ideal.

00:22:45.150 --> 00:22:49.030
I think, in this instance,
it's also the case

00:22:49.030 --> 00:22:53.350
that courts tend to be
establishment focused,

00:22:53.350 --> 00:22:57.430
you don't get to be a judge
by being a rebel, right?

00:22:57.430 --> 00:23:02.430
You, so courts are establishment oriented,

00:23:02.500 --> 00:23:04.930
whether they're, whether
a judge is appointed

00:23:04.930 --> 00:23:08.090
by a Democrat, or a Republican,

00:23:08.090 --> 00:23:10.710
they have an interest in the status quo,

00:23:10.710 --> 00:23:13.570
the law has an interest in
preserving the status quo,

00:23:13.570 --> 00:23:15.738
and making sure that people, you know,

00:23:15.738 --> 00:23:18.480
can sort of plan their
lives, go about their lives

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:20.360
without getting too disrupted.

00:23:20.360 --> 00:23:24.380
And President Trump
doesn't seem to care all

00:23:24.380 --> 00:23:26.690
that much about the status quo,

00:23:26.690 --> 00:23:30.660
and he is quite, in
virtually every respect,

00:23:30.660 --> 00:23:33.093
a challenge to the status quo.

00:23:34.150 --> 00:23:38.950
And in his attitudes towards
constitutional norms,

00:23:38.950 --> 00:23:43.123
constitutional rights, and,
indeed, the courts themselves,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:49.840
he is not only threatening
the rights of individuals,

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:53.823
but threatening the
institutional role of courts.

00:23:55.060 --> 00:23:59.200
So when the first nationwide

00:24:01.513 --> 00:24:02.800
ban on the,

00:24:02.800 --> 00:24:07.800
travel ban was issued by the
judge in Washington state,

00:24:08.230 --> 00:24:10.950
Trump tweeted, and referred

00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:15.270
to the judge as a "so-called
judge," all right?

00:24:15.270 --> 00:24:18.083
So when the president is,

00:24:21.090 --> 00:24:25.197
shows utter disregard
for basic underpinnings

00:24:26.327 --> 00:24:29.320
and foundations of our
constitutional system,

00:24:29.320 --> 00:24:31.760
it is not surprising

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:36.450
that courts will be
part of the resistance,

00:24:36.450 --> 00:24:39.650
and indeed, they have, they have stood up

00:24:39.650 --> 00:24:44.650
for the rule of law, for
rights, at least thus far,

00:24:44.650 --> 00:24:47.603
against the, against the president.

00:24:50.360 --> 00:24:51.250
But

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:54.740
courts are

00:24:54.740 --> 00:24:56.943
by no means enough,

00:24:57.890 --> 00:25:01.430
and it's not these, this
handful of decisions

00:25:01.430 --> 00:25:04.893
that really makes me hopeful,

00:25:06.300 --> 00:25:08.813
you know, it is,

00:25:08.813 --> 00:25:12.970
it is much more the other forms of checks

00:25:12.970 --> 00:25:16.580
and balances that operate at a time

00:25:16.580 --> 00:25:21.580
when one party controls the
executive, the Congress,

00:25:22.580 --> 00:25:25.990
the Supreme Court, and, while we're at it,

00:25:25.990 --> 00:25:29.023
two thirds of the state,
of state governments.

00:25:30.190 --> 00:25:31.640
And that is

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:35.733
not formal separation of powers,

00:25:37.190 --> 00:25:38.060
but

00:25:38.060 --> 00:25:42.090
the informal checks and balances

00:25:42.090 --> 00:25:43.913
of civil society,

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:47.933
the press, the academy,

00:25:50.334 --> 00:25:53.990
and religious organizations,

00:25:53.990 --> 00:25:58.080
and civil society
non-profit organizations,

00:25:58.080 --> 00:26:01.233
like the ACLU, or Planned Parenthood.

00:26:02.940 --> 00:26:07.180
At times like this, those are

00:26:07.180 --> 00:26:08.260
critical

00:26:09.560 --> 00:26:14.560
potential sites of resistance,
indeed, that's why,

00:26:14.710 --> 00:26:18.063
when authoritarians take power,

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:21.540
and exercise authoritarian control,

00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:23.750
don't just walk and talk
like an authoritarian,

00:26:23.750 --> 00:26:28.750
but rule like an authoritarian,
as we've seen in Hungary,

00:26:29.720 --> 00:26:33.673
in Poland, these are their targets,

00:26:34.600 --> 00:26:35.720
right, they target the courts,

00:26:35.720 --> 00:26:38.130
but they also target the universities,

00:26:38.130 --> 00:26:41.630
they target the press,
they target civil society,

00:26:41.630 --> 00:26:44.940
because they, and they
often target religion,

00:26:44.940 --> 00:26:49.940
because these are all places
where citizens come together

00:26:50.680 --> 00:26:53.240
and act collectively in ways

00:26:53.240 --> 00:26:55.610
that can hold the government accountable,

00:26:55.610 --> 00:26:59.653
and can resist abuses of authority.

00:27:01.200 --> 00:27:05.740
This is why the first
amendment is so important,

00:27:05.740 --> 00:27:10.100
it's not just, the first
amendment doesn't just protect

00:27:10.100 --> 00:27:15.100
a right to express yourself,
to discover who you are,

00:27:18.243 --> 00:27:21.620
to be an autonomous human being,

00:27:21.620 --> 00:27:23.873
it protects that value, to be sure.

00:27:24.790 --> 00:27:28.540
But it also is a critical,
plays a critical structural role

00:27:28.540 --> 00:27:32.190
in checking abuse, and it does that

00:27:32.190 --> 00:27:34.460
by protecting precisely

00:27:35.360 --> 00:27:39.760
these forms of civil
society checks and balances,

00:27:39.760 --> 00:27:43.590
a free press, free exercise of religion,

00:27:43.590 --> 00:27:47.720
freedom of speech, freedom of association,

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:49.420
and freedom of assembly,

00:27:49.420 --> 00:27:53.983
this is how the people hold
a government accountable.

00:27:55.060 --> 00:28:00.060
And what I find most encouraging
about the, the Trump era,

00:28:02.010 --> 00:28:02.843
is

00:28:02.843 --> 00:28:05.710
how energized

00:28:05.710 --> 00:28:10.180
that civil society sector is.

