works.

00:33:15.060 --> 00:33:15.910
So

00:33:16.960 --> 00:33:20.543
let's, let's, you know,
think back to the Muslim ban.

00:33:21.610 --> 00:33:26.610
The Muslim ban was President
Trump's first major initiative,

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:31.030
and that was not a coincidence, he chose,

00:33:31.030 --> 00:33:33.960
for his first major
initiative, it was issued

00:33:33.960 --> 00:33:38.563
on January 26th, six days
after he took office,

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:44.323
targeting foreign nationals,

00:33:46.090 --> 00:33:50.940
targeting Muslim foreign
nationals in the name

00:33:50.940 --> 00:33:55.300
of protecting American's
national security.

00:33:55.300 --> 00:33:58.274
Now, historically,

00:33:58.274 --> 00:34:03.190
that kind of measure does pretty well,

00:34:03.190 --> 00:34:06.230
politically, in the United States,

00:34:06.230 --> 00:34:08.140
and in other countries, as well, that is,

00:34:08.140 --> 00:34:11.900
if the government says to the people, hey,

00:34:11.900 --> 00:34:16.000
you're under threat,
we're here to protect you,

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:21.000
and we're not gonna take
away your rights to do this,

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:24.160
we're gonna take away the
rights of somebody else,

00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:26.530
and the somebody else are foreigners,

00:34:26.530 --> 00:34:29.653
and not just foreigners,
but Muslim foreigners.

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:36.420
In the aftermath of 9/11, President Bush

00:34:36.420 --> 00:34:40.560
and the Justice Department rounded up

00:34:40.560 --> 00:34:44.780
over 5,000 foreign nationals,

00:34:44.780 --> 00:34:47.220
Arab and Muslim foreign nationals,

00:34:47.220 --> 00:34:50.240
and detained them on suspicion

00:34:50.240 --> 00:34:51.900
that they might be involved with 9/11.

00:34:51.900 --> 00:34:54.770
None of them turned out
to be involved with 9/11,

00:34:54.770 --> 00:34:58.730
but it wasn't, it didn't cause an outcry,

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:02.900
and the message was, we're targeting them,

00:35:02.900 --> 00:35:05.850
not you, and we're seeking to protect you.

00:35:05.850 --> 00:35:07.770
The same thing happened in 1920,

00:35:07.770 --> 00:35:10.123
when there were a series
of terrorist bombings,

00:35:11.110 --> 00:35:14.180
this is as close as I get
to Thomas Jefferson, 1920,

00:35:14.180 --> 00:35:16.510
there were a series of terrorist
bombings, and the response

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:20.530
to those terrorist bombings
was the Palmer Raids,

00:35:20.530 --> 00:35:22.350
in which the government went out,

00:35:22.350 --> 00:35:24.700
and rounded up thousands
of foreign nationals,

00:35:24.700 --> 00:35:29.700
none of whom had anything to
do with the terrorist bombings.

00:35:29.970 --> 00:35:34.773
And again, not a huge outcry
from the American people.

00:35:36.340 --> 00:35:39.123
But this time was very different,

00:35:41.028 --> 00:35:44.910
this time there was
resistance from day one.

00:35:46.450 --> 00:35:49.300
The order was issued on a Friday,

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:54.300
that night we filed the
first case challenging

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:56.800
the,

00:35:56.800 --> 00:35:57.910
the ban,

00:35:57.910 --> 00:36:00.650
on behalf of two young

00:36:01.670 --> 00:36:04.890
Iraqi men who had been

00:36:04.890 --> 00:36:08.470
given visas to come here after working

00:36:08.470 --> 00:36:11.593
with our military in Iraq.

00:36:13.170 --> 00:36:16.380
They were stopped at JFK
airport, because they were

00:36:16.380 --> 00:36:19.620
from Iraq, and the Muslim ban
covered anyone who was coming

00:36:19.620 --> 00:36:23.020
from Iraq, even those who had
visas, who had been vetted,

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:25.300
who had been cleared, and
who'd been given visas

00:36:25.300 --> 00:36:28.890
because they had sacrificed for us.

00:36:28.890 --> 00:36:33.332
And so we sued that
night, with the help of a,

00:36:33.332 --> 00:36:36.763
of a clinic of law students
at Yale Law School.

00:36:38.010 --> 00:36:42.343
And the next day, Saturday,
a remarkable thing happened.

00:36:43.420 --> 00:36:47.810
Tens of thousands of Americans rushed out

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:52.690
to airports to demonstrate,
and this was remarkable

00:36:52.690 --> 00:36:54.703
for at least two reasons, one,

00:36:55.770 --> 00:36:58.830
this was not the way
we historically respond

00:36:58.830 --> 00:37:02.303
when the government
targets them to protect us.

00:37:03.450 --> 00:37:06.400
People were going out to airports not

00:37:06.400 --> 00:37:08.920
to demonstrate for their own rights,

00:37:08.920 --> 00:37:11.230
but for the rights of
others, for the rights

00:37:11.230 --> 00:37:14.450
of foreign nationals, for
the rights of Muslims.

00:37:14.450 --> 00:37:17.220
But the second thing that
makes it remarkable is

00:37:17.220 --> 00:37:19.310
where these demonstrations took place,

00:37:19.310 --> 00:37:22.730
they were at airports,
I don't know about you,

00:37:22.730 --> 00:37:25.080
but the last place I want to be,

00:37:25.080 --> 00:37:28.650
unless I have to go somewhere,
is an airport, right?

00:37:28.650 --> 00:37:32.320
It's a soul crushing environment, and yet,

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:35.460
tens of thousands of Americans
got off their couches,

00:37:35.460 --> 00:37:40.460
and went out to demonstrate,
to protest on behalf

00:37:40.750 --> 00:37:45.330
of the other, and against
the Trump travel ban.

00:37:45.330 --> 00:37:49.530
They went to airports like
JFK, and Boston Logan Airport,

00:37:49.530 --> 00:37:51.430
and SFO, where there's plenty

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:53.700
of international flights coming in,

00:37:53.700 --> 00:37:55.440
and people were getting stopped.

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:58.050
But they also went out to
wholly domestic airports,

00:37:58.050 --> 00:38:01.350
where there were no international
travelers whatsoever,

00:38:01.350 --> 00:38:06.350
people were just, people
were primed, and ready to,

00:38:06.350 --> 00:38:09.963
to stand up, and to act, to engage.

00:38:11.490 --> 00:38:15.590
And it wasn't just, it wasn't just people,

00:38:15.590 --> 00:38:19.820
ordinary people, it was also
all manner of civil society,

00:38:19.820 --> 00:38:22.950
so ultimately, the leading, the presidents

00:38:22.950 --> 00:38:24.830
of all the leading universities signed

00:38:24.830 --> 00:38:27.180
a letter opposing the Trump ban,

00:38:27.180 --> 00:38:30.560
the leading science
organizations all signed

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:33.733
a petition opposing the Trump ban, the,

00:38:35.693 --> 00:38:40.693
the CEOs of the largest and
most successful corporations

00:38:41.060 --> 00:38:44.090
in Silicon Valley
submitted an amicus brief

00:38:44.090 --> 00:38:46.740
opposing the Trump travel ban.

00:38:46.740 --> 00:38:51.740
And even national security
officials came together

00:38:52.120 --> 00:38:55.790
to oppose the Trump
travel ban, that weekend,

00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:56.983
Michael Hayden,

00:38:58.670 --> 00:38:59.853
who was a,

00:39:01.100 --> 00:39:03.350
the head of the NSA and the CIA,

00:39:03.350 --> 00:39:07.600
under George W. Bush,
he's a, he's a defender

00:39:07.600 --> 00:39:11.370
of the CIA's interrogation
slash torture program,

00:39:11.370 --> 00:39:14.210
I've debated him on
several occasions on that,

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:16.037
and yet, that weekend, he tweeted,

00:39:16.037 --> 00:39:19.917
"How about that, ACLU
and I in same corner."

00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:26.423
Dick Cheney said this was
un-American, Dick Cheney.

00:39:26.423 --> 00:39:27.860
(audience laughs)

00:39:27.860 --> 00:39:32.860
And Berkeley's own John
Yoo, who came to prominence

00:39:32.940 --> 00:39:36.330
by writing the memos as a lawyer

00:39:36.330 --> 00:39:38.890
in the Justice Department
that authorized the use

00:39:38.890 --> 00:39:42.310
of torture by President Bush,

00:39:42.310 --> 00:39:45.277
he wrote an oped for The
New York Times, saying,

00:39:45.277 --> 00:39:49.420
"This time executive
power has gone too far."

00:39:49.420 --> 00:39:51.320
So there was a remarkable

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:57.370
voicing of resistance from people,

00:39:57.370 --> 00:40:01.576
from ordinary citizens at airports,

00:40:01.576 --> 00:40:05.730
to the leading university,
scientific organizations,

00:40:05.730 --> 00:40:10.293
businesses, and former
government officials.

00:40:12.090 --> 00:40:17.090
We had a, that was all on that
weekend, so that, our case

00:40:19.251 --> 00:40:21.503
that we filed that Friday night,

00:40:22.430 --> 00:40:25.270
was scheduled for an emergency hearing on

00:40:25.270 --> 00:40:27.023
that Saturday night,

00:40:29.381 --> 00:40:31.760
and it went out on Twitter,

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:34.540
as these things do,
that there was a hearing

00:40:34.540 --> 00:40:37.200
on the Muslim ban, on Saturday night,

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:40.880
at the Brooklyn Federal
Courthouse, and this was the scene,

00:40:40.880 --> 00:40:43.590
I'm gonna see if this works,
this was the scene outside

00:40:43.590 --> 00:40:46.373
of the courthouse.

00:40:48.945 --> 00:40:52.970
- [Crowd] ACLU, we are
here, we stand with you!

00:40:52.970 --> 00:40:57.250
- Over 1,000 people
surrounded the courthouse

00:40:57.250 --> 00:41:00.040
on a Saturday night, like, you know,

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:02.007
how often do you think
on a Saturday night,

00:41:02.007 --> 00:41:03.617
"Hey, what do you want to
do, it's a Saturday night,

00:41:03.617 --> 00:41:06.170
"let's go down to the courthouse."

00:41:06.170 --> 00:41:08.480
They came and surrounded the courthouse,

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:11.760
it was a cold night, January 27th,

00:41:11.760 --> 00:41:14.324
it was almost as cold as it is here today.

00:41:14.324 --> 00:41:15.801
(audience laughs)

00:41:15.801 --> 00:41:17.627
And they were chanting, "ACLU,

00:41:19.907 --> 00:41:22.740
"we are here, we stand with you."

00:41:22.740 --> 00:41:27.193
Again, never in the history
of the ACLU has that happened,

00:41:28.090 --> 00:41:32.970
and indeed, shortly thereafter,
the ACLU lawyers walked out

00:41:32.970 --> 00:41:35.730
of the courthouse to announce to the crowd

00:41:35.730 --> 00:41:37.030
that the judge has issued

00:41:37.030 --> 00:41:42.030
the first injunction
against the travel ban.

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:46.323
So, and these things are not,

00:41:46.323 --> 00:41:48.590
and then, then the court

00:41:48.590 --> 00:41:52.830
in Washington state
issued the nationwide ban,

00:41:52.830 --> 00:41:55.800
and then those cases went up on appeal,

00:41:55.800 --> 00:41:59.440
and the Courts of Appeals
affirmed those injunctions,

00:41:59.440 --> 00:42:03.080
and Trump initially
made all kinds of noises

00:42:03.080 --> 00:42:04.840
about appealing, but ultimately decided

00:42:04.840 --> 00:42:07.330
to put out a second version
of the ban, and that, too,

00:42:07.330 --> 00:42:10.270
was struck down, and he's took
that up to the Supreme Court,

00:42:10.270 --> 00:42:12.410
but then just as the court
was to hear argument in

00:42:12.410 --> 00:42:16.205
that case, he put out a
third version of the ban.

00:42:16.205 --> 00:42:19.800
And that one has been
challenged in the courts,

00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:22.760
as well, and has been struck
down by district courts,

00:42:22.760 --> 00:42:25.410
by the Court of Appeals
in the Ninth Circuit here,

00:42:25.410 --> 00:42:27.130
and the Court of Appeals
for the Fourth Circuit

00:42:27.130 --> 00:42:29.887
in Richmond, Virginia, and will be heard

00:42:29.887 --> 00:42:32.630
in the Supreme Court.

00:42:32.630 --> 00:42:36.700
So this is an example, I think, of this,

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:40.800
the combination of civil society activism

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:45.310
and courts playing a
critically effective role

00:42:45.310 --> 00:42:48.970
in checking the president's abuses.

00:42:48.970 --> 00:42:51.973
And if you look at, at history,

00:42:53.590 --> 00:42:58.420
what you often see is that dark times

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:01.060
can lead us to positive results

00:43:02.190 --> 00:43:03.500
if,

00:43:03.500 --> 00:43:05.830
if people respond

00:43:05.830 --> 00:43:10.390
to those dark times by
engaging, by resisting,

00:43:10.390 --> 00:43:13.080
and by acting collectively
through civil society

00:43:13.080 --> 00:43:17.320
to advance a brighter future.

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:19.510
So the first take, the first amendment,

00:43:19.510 --> 00:43:24.450
the first amendment today
is pretty well settled,

00:43:24.450 --> 00:43:27.120
there is a very strong presumption

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:30.160
that the government cannot
suppress your speech,

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:33.150
even if you're advocating crime,

00:43:33.150 --> 00:43:36.010
unless your speech is,

00:43:36.010 --> 00:43:37.830
is intended and likely

00:43:37.830 --> 00:43:42.830
to produce imminent criminal
conduct, a very high bar.

00:43:45.180 --> 00:43:48.030
It was established in a
case involving the KKK,

00:43:48.030 --> 00:43:52.170
Brandenburg versus Ohio, 1960s.

00:43:52.170 --> 00:43:55.390
Similarly, it is established
that you have a right

00:43:55.390 --> 00:43:57.860
to associate even with organizations

00:43:57.860 --> 00:43:59.793
that engage in criminal activity,

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:05.650
as long as you don't specifically intend

00:44:05.650 --> 00:44:09.403
to further the illegal
ends of the organization.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.780
That, too, was established in the 1960s

00:44:12.780 --> 00:44:16.620
in a series of Communist Party cases.

00:44:16.620 --> 00:44:18.300
The argument of the government had been

00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:21.840
the Communist Party engages
in illegal activity,

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:23.270
it seeks to overthrow the United States

00:44:23.270 --> 00:44:25.230
by force and violence, that's a crime,

00:44:25.230 --> 00:44:26.660
and therefore anyone who's associated

00:44:26.660 --> 00:44:30.340
with the Communist Party
can be denied their job,

00:44:30.340 --> 00:44:35.110
can be locked up, punished,
deported, et cetera.

00:44:35.110 --> 00:44:38.560
But ultimately, the court ruled no,

00:44:38.560 --> 00:44:40.756
you have a right to join
the Communist Party,

00:44:40.756 --> 00:44:41.740
you have a right to support
the Communist Party,

00:44:41.740 --> 00:44:44.370
as long as you don't specifically intend

00:44:44.370 --> 00:44:46.050
to further its illegal ends.

00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:50.590
So those are tremendously
significant protections

00:44:50.590 --> 00:44:55.150
of our first amendment
freedoms, but they came out,

00:44:55.150 --> 00:44:57.150
where did they come from?

00:44:57.150 --> 00:45:02.150
They came from a history
of government abuse

00:45:02.290 --> 00:45:07.290
of first amendment rights,
they came from decades

00:45:07.730 --> 00:45:11.530
of the McCarthy era, and the red scare,

00:45:11.530 --> 00:45:16.530
and the targeting of anti-war
activists during World War I,

00:45:17.850 --> 00:45:22.020
and the targeting of anarchists in the,

00:45:22.020 --> 00:45:27.020
in the teens and the 1920s, and
it was out of the experience

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:28.560
of abuse

00:45:29.820 --> 00:45:32.880
that the court ultimately adopted

00:45:32.880 --> 00:45:37.383
a powerfully protective
view of the first amendment.

00:45:38.390 --> 00:45:40.950
And it, the court didn't do it on its own,

00:45:40.950 --> 00:45:45.050
it was through the work of labor unions,

00:45:45.050 --> 00:45:47.930
of the Communist Party, of organizations

00:45:47.930 --> 00:45:49.750
that represented the Communist Party,

00:45:49.750 --> 00:45:51.120
the National Lawyers Guild,

00:45:51.120 --> 00:45:53.780
and the National Emergency
Civil Liberties Committee,

00:45:53.780 --> 00:45:56.520
of organizations like the ACLU

00:45:56.520 --> 00:45:59.220
to advance a broader protection,

00:45:59.220 --> 00:46:01.870
broader understanding of
first amendment protections.

00:46:02.900 --> 00:46:04.800
In my book, Engines of Liberty,

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:08.980
which I wrote the year
before I joined the ACLU,

00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:12.727
I looked at a couple other
examples, one is the,

00:46:14.550 --> 00:46:18.320
how did the right to bear arms

00:46:19.680 --> 00:46:24.150
go from being dismissed as a fraud in 1990

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:27.210
by the Chief Justice of the
Supreme Court, Warren Berger,

00:46:27.210 --> 00:46:30.317
a conservative Republican
appointee, who said that,

00:46:30.317 --> 00:46:32.137
"The notion that the
second amendment protects

00:46:32.137 --> 00:46:34.387
"an individual right to bear arms is one

00:46:34.387 --> 00:46:36.227
"of the greatest frauds perpetrated

00:46:36.227 --> 00:46:41.227
"on the American people in
my lifetime," that was 1990.

00:46:41.990 --> 00:46:45.500
How did it go from being
dismissed as a fraud

00:46:45.500 --> 00:46:47.500
by a conservative Supreme Court justice

00:46:47.500 --> 00:46:52.390
to being recognized as a
constitutional right just less

00:46:52.390 --> 00:46:54.843
than two decades later, in 2008?

00:46:56.170 --> 00:46:58.693
And what the answer is,

00:47:00.190 --> 00:47:05.120
as you, I'm sure, know, the
National Rifle Association.

00:47:05.120 --> 00:47:09.500
It was the work of the
NRA, a group of citizens,

00:47:09.500 --> 00:47:13.450
committed to a particular
vision of constitutional law,

00:47:13.450 --> 00:47:14.830
one that had been dismissed

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:17.050
by the Supreme Court as fraudulent,

00:47:17.050 --> 00:47:19.220
one that had been rejected
by the federal courts

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:24.220
for 100 years, it was their
work, their political work

00:47:25.490 --> 00:47:29.370
that led, that created the possibility

00:47:30.360 --> 00:47:33.210
that this right could be recognized.

00:47:33.210 --> 00:47:38.210
And what, what sparked their
engagement in this quest?

00:47:40.690 --> 00:47:42.690
The NRA has been around for a long time,

00:47:42.690 --> 00:47:44.880
but the NRA has not been
a political organization

00:47:44.880 --> 00:47:47.110
for a long time, the NRA started out,

00:47:47.110 --> 00:47:49.380
was founded after the Civil War

00:47:49.380 --> 00:47:51.960
by Union generals who were abashed

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:56.200
at how bad shots the Union Army was,

00:47:56.200 --> 00:47:58.140
and so they created the NRA to, like,

00:47:58.140 --> 00:48:00.760
train people to be better marksmen.

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:03.580
And it was a marksmanship
and hunting organization

00:48:03.580 --> 00:48:07.820
for, you know, over 100
years, then, in the '60s,

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:11.780
there was the uprisings, and the violence,

00:48:11.780 --> 00:48:15.380
and the assassinations, and it led 1968

00:48:15.380 --> 00:48:20.260
to the most aggressive federal
gun control legislation

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:23.750
in American history, the
Gun Control Act of 1968.

00:48:23.750 --> 00:48:26.763
And it was only in response to that,

00:48:27.710 --> 00:48:32.710
considered a disaster by
the NRA and its members,

00:48:33.030 --> 00:48:35.620
that they created a political arm,

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:38.570
and undertook a political campaign,

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:41.850
which was designed to instantiate

00:48:41.850 --> 00:48:44.020
and establish an individual
right to bear arms.

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:48.240
And they did it incrementally,
they did it in the states,

00:48:48.240 --> 00:48:50.720
they did it through legislation,

00:48:50.720 --> 00:48:52.720
they did it through electoral politics,

00:48:52.720 --> 00:48:57.720
they did it by arguing cases
in state court, and they,

00:48:58.420 --> 00:49:01.300
and ultimately, they were able to

00:49:02.250 --> 00:49:04.810
put, get all 50 states

00:49:04.810 --> 00:49:08.220
on board as protecting an
individual right to bear arms

00:49:08.220 --> 00:49:11.610
by the time the Supreme Court
took up the question in 2008.

00:49:11.610 --> 00:49:13.640
So under state law, or
state constitutions,

00:49:13.640 --> 00:49:15.760
the states had already
recognized an individual right

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:19.900
to bear arms, they got
Congress to support the notion

00:49:19.900 --> 00:49:22.020
of an individual right to
bear arms in several pieces

00:49:22.020 --> 00:49:25.510
of legislation, they
got the executive branch

00:49:25.510 --> 00:49:27.510
to support an individual
right to bear arms

00:49:27.510 --> 00:49:29.630
when George Bush was
elected with their support,

00:49:29.630 --> 00:49:31.700
and John Ashcroft was
made the Attorney General,

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:33.460
a longtime NRA member,

00:49:33.460 --> 00:49:35.843
and they immediately wrote the
Attorney General, and said,

00:49:35.843 --> 00:49:37.753
"Dear John, what do you think

00:49:37.753 --> 00:49:40.167
"about the Justice
Department's longtime view

00:49:40.167 --> 00:49:41.737
"that the second amendment doesn't protect

00:49:41.737 --> 00:49:44.060
"an individual right to bear arms?"

00:49:44.060 --> 00:49:45.357
And he wrote back immediately, and said,

00:49:45.357 --> 00:49:49.240
"I think it's crazy," and
he reversed a position

00:49:49.240 --> 00:49:51.050
that the Justice Department
had taken for decades,

00:49:51.050 --> 00:49:54.220
and got a 100 page memo written

00:49:54.220 --> 00:49:55.870
by the Office of Legal Counsel

00:49:55.870 --> 00:49:58.850
on why there is an individual
right to bear arms.

00:49:58.850 --> 00:50:02.540
And so when the case came up
to the Supreme Court in 2008,

00:50:02.540 --> 00:50:06.520
the NRA had already succeeded
in getting the states,

00:50:06.520 --> 00:50:08.900
the Congress, and the executive branch

00:50:08.900 --> 00:50:11.320
to endorse this concept, not that hard,

00:50:11.320 --> 00:50:12.930
then, to get the Supreme Court to do it.

00:50:12.930 --> 00:50:17.930
But what sparked them to do
it was, from their standpoint,

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:23.060
a loss, a big loss in the Gun Control Act.

00:50:23.060 --> 00:50:28.060
So they, the NRA understands
the democratic underpinnings

00:50:28.420 --> 00:50:31.650
of constitutional rights,
another story I tell

00:50:31.650 --> 00:50:36.030
in that book is the story of
the marriage equality folks.

00:50:36.030 --> 00:50:39.180
How did marriage equality
go from unthinkable,

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:42.230
which is what it was in, 25 years ago,

00:50:42.230 --> 00:50:44.590
to inevitable, which
is what it was in 2015,

00:50:44.590 --> 00:50:48.030
when the Supreme Court
decided that there indeed is

00:50:48.030 --> 00:50:50.230
a constitutional right
to marriage equality?

00:50:51.070 --> 00:50:55.080
And the answer is the same, the NRA, no,

00:50:55.080 --> 00:50:58.960
the answer is the same, it is
civil society organizations,

00:50:58.960 --> 00:51:03.670
who took a vision that
was rejected in the law,

00:51:03.670 --> 00:51:07.990
and worked in a variety
of forums, through people,

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:10.860
to advance a different conception

00:51:10.860 --> 00:51:13.540
that made it possible
to prevail on the claim.

00:51:13.540 --> 00:51:16.850
So, in 1972, a gay couple argued

00:51:16.850 --> 00:51:19.300
that they had a right to be married,

00:51:19.300 --> 00:51:21.300
and they relied on the
equal protection clause

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:23.300
of the constitution, and
the due process clause

00:51:23.300 --> 00:51:25.560
of the constitution, and
the Supreme Court thought

00:51:25.560 --> 00:51:28.460
so little of the argument
that they dismissed it

00:51:28.460 --> 00:51:29.467
with a single sentence, and said,

00:51:29.467 --> 00:51:33.670
"It doesn't even raise a serious
question," that was 1972.

00:51:33.670 --> 00:51:36.950
2015, the court recognized
a constitutional right

00:51:36.950 --> 00:51:39.490
to marry, on the basis of what?

00:51:39.490 --> 00:51:42.150
Equal protection, and
the due process clause,

00:51:42.150 --> 00:51:46.683
the exact same arguments, so
the arguments didn't change,

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:50.300
the court, the court changed, right,

00:51:50.300 --> 00:51:53.750
the court in 2015 was different
from the court in 1972,

00:51:53.750 --> 00:51:57.540
but if anything, the court
in 2015 was more conservative

00:51:57.540 --> 00:51:59.790
than the court in 1972,
that was the tail end

00:51:59.790 --> 00:52:02.253
of the Warren court.

00:52:03.697 --> 00:52:07.910
2015 was, you know, the Roberts court,

00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:13.860
and yet, the court in 2015
recognized the right, so the law,

00:52:13.860 --> 00:52:17.300
the legal arguments didn't
change, the court, if anything,

00:52:17.300 --> 00:52:19.530
changed to become more conservative,

00:52:19.530 --> 00:52:22.640
so what explains the change?

00:52:22.640 --> 00:52:25.370
What explains the change
is the world changed,

00:52:25.370 --> 00:52:27.560
and how did the world
change, the world changed

00:52:27.560 --> 00:52:29.850
because groups like
Lambda Legal Defense Fund,

00:52:29.850 --> 00:52:33.670
Freedom to Marry, gay and
lesbian advocates and defenders,

00:52:33.670 --> 00:52:36.830
the ACLU Gay and Lesbian Rights Project,

00:52:36.830 --> 00:52:40.840
worked collectively,
incrementally, patiently,

00:52:42.200 --> 00:52:45.290
over 30 years to establish

00:52:47.060 --> 00:52:49.420
steps on the road

00:52:49.420 --> 00:52:51.660
to recognizing marriage equality.

00:52:51.660 --> 00:52:54.080
And they didn't go for
it in one fell swoop,

00:52:54.080 --> 00:52:57.570
they did in incrementally,
they started in the states,

00:52:57.570 --> 00:52:59.360
they got progressive cities

00:52:59.360 --> 00:53:02.430
to recognize domestic
partnerships for gay couples,

00:53:02.430 --> 00:53:04.820
they got progressive counties

00:53:04.820 --> 00:53:06.500
to pass anti-discrimination laws

00:53:06.500 --> 00:53:10.240
that included sexual
orientation, they got some courts

00:53:10.240 --> 00:53:15.240
and some progressive states
to recognize gay families in,

00:53:15.810 --> 00:53:19.283
under family law, and
adoption rules, and the like.

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:23.230
And only then did they make an argument

00:53:23.230 --> 00:53:25.980
that there's a right to marriage,

00:53:25.980 --> 00:53:28.003
and they made it first in Vermont,

00:53:28.990 --> 00:53:32.423
in a state court, on state
constitutional grounds,

00:53:33.728 --> 00:53:36.840
and, and won civil unions there,

00:53:36.840 --> 00:53:38.270
and then took it to Massachusetts,

00:53:38.270 --> 00:53:41.290
and made the same, same
arguments in Massachusetts

00:53:41.290 --> 00:53:42.830
on state constitutional grounds,

00:53:42.830 --> 00:53:44.270
not federal constitutional grounds,

00:53:44.270 --> 00:53:46.640
'cause if they made a federal
constitutional argument,

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:48.180
it could go to the Supreme Court,

00:53:48.180 --> 00:53:50.040
where they knew they would lose.

00:53:50.040 --> 00:53:51.570
And so they kept it to the states,

00:53:51.570 --> 00:53:54.500
where the, the state
supreme court is the final,

00:53:54.500 --> 00:53:56.970
is the final arbiter.

00:53:56.970 --> 00:53:59.920
But there, too, what, what sort

00:53:59.920 --> 00:54:02.460
of launched this whole movement

00:54:02.460 --> 00:54:06.973
for gay rights was a series of losses,

00:54:08.130 --> 00:54:10.970
the murder, the homophobic murder

00:54:10.970 --> 00:54:14.820
of Matthew Shepard, the AIDs crisis,

00:54:14.820 --> 00:54:16.980
and the failure and
refusal of the government

00:54:16.980 --> 00:54:20.220
to do enough to respond to a crisis

00:54:20.220 --> 00:54:23.430
that was specifically affecting,

00:54:23.430 --> 00:54:26.513
at that time, anyway, the gay community.

00:54:27.750 --> 00:54:31.080
Along the way, proposition eight, right,

00:54:31.080 --> 00:54:33.420
which people in this room remember,

00:54:33.420 --> 00:54:36.010
proposition eight, when the Supreme Court

00:54:36.010 --> 00:54:38.200
of California recognized
marriage equality,

00:54:38.200 --> 00:54:41.940
it was put on the ballot, and in 2008,

00:54:41.940 --> 00:54:43.850
in the most liberal state in the country,

00:54:43.850 --> 00:54:47.100
maybe except for Vermont, California,

00:54:47.100 --> 00:54:50.270
in a year when Barack Obama was elected,

00:54:50.270 --> 00:54:52.580
the first black president was elected,

00:54:52.580 --> 00:54:54.493
marriage equality lost,

00:54:55.440 --> 00:54:58.920
lost in a popular
referendum in California.

00:54:58.920 --> 00:55:01.363
That was a devastating loss, but it,

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:07.133
it sparked a renewed
commitment to engage in

00:55:08.263 --> 00:55:12.707
activism to advance the
notion of marriage equality,

00:55:12.707 --> 00:55:17.090
and it caused the groups to
reconsider how they were arguing

00:55:17.090 --> 00:55:21.360
for marriage equality, and
shifting from a rights framework

00:55:21.360 --> 00:55:23.900
in their arguments to a love
and commitment framework,

00:55:23.900 --> 00:55:26.550
which was much, turned out
to be much more effective

00:55:26.550 --> 00:55:29.250
at bringing persuadable people,

00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:33.460
people on the fence to their side.

00:55:33.460 --> 00:55:35.940
So, so dark times

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:37.820
can often

00:55:38.700 --> 00:55:40.470
inspire

00:55:40.470 --> 00:55:43.500
people to come together and act in ways

00:55:43.500 --> 00:55:47.610
that, advance the ball
from their perspective,

00:55:47.610 --> 00:55:50.140
whether it's an ACLU and
first amendment rights,

00:55:50.140 --> 00:55:53.543
whether it's the NRA, and
the right to bear arms,

00:55:54.654 --> 00:55:56.970
or gay rights groups,

00:55:56.970 --> 00:55:58.913
and marriage equality.

00:55:59.920 --> 00:56:00.753
So,

00:56:02.150 --> 00:56:05.633
so in a very real sense,

00:56:06.680 --> 00:56:11.680
how this period will
ultimately be seen is up to us.

00:56:12.070 --> 00:56:15.190
It is possible that this is the first step

00:56:15.190 --> 00:56:19.130
on the road to authoritarianism
in the United States,

00:56:19.130 --> 00:56:22.010
certainly Donald Trump
exhibits all the features

00:56:22.010 --> 00:56:26.650
of authoritarian leaders,
but it is also possible

00:56:26.650 --> 00:56:29.150
that we will look back
on this period 10 years

00:56:29.150 --> 00:56:34.150
from now as a dark time that, nonetheless,

00:56:34.570 --> 00:56:38.490
inspired and catalyzed the citizenry

00:56:38.490 --> 00:56:39.840
to step up

00:56:39.840 --> 00:56:43.300
and speak out in favor of

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:47.710
visions of civil rights
and civil liberties

00:56:47.710 --> 00:56:52.553
that reflect this country
at its, at its best.

00:56:53.560 --> 00:56:55.960
And I think we've seen many signs of that,

00:56:55.960 --> 00:56:58.880
the most recent sign of that, I think,

00:56:58.880 --> 00:57:02.750
is the high school
students who've responded

00:57:02.750 --> 00:57:06.830
to the mass shooting in Florida, how?

00:57:06.830 --> 00:57:10.033
By engaging in citizen activism,

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:15.120
and it's quite possible that they will

00:57:15.120 --> 00:57:18.250
shift the debate

00:57:18.250 --> 00:57:21.230
on gun rights and gun control

00:57:22.080 --> 00:57:26.670
in a direction that favors a gun control,

00:57:26.670 --> 00:57:31.670
but the very willingness of
them to get out there and speak,

00:57:32.240 --> 00:57:34.530
this is not the first shooting,

00:57:34.530 --> 00:57:38.610
mass shooting at a high
school, the very willingness

00:57:38.610 --> 00:57:42.270
of them to take this action
up in their own hands,

00:57:42.270 --> 00:57:46.170
in their own voices, I
think is a reflection

00:57:46.170 --> 00:57:50.670
of what they have seen since
Donald Trump was elected,

00:57:50.670 --> 00:57:53.520
in the women's march, in
the airport demonstrations,

00:57:53.520 --> 00:57:55.923
in the DACA demonstrations,

00:57:55.923 --> 00:58:00.923
in the town halls around the
ACA, in the special elections,

00:58:01.620 --> 00:58:06.620
and now, in the effort
to advance gun control.

00:58:08.090 --> 00:58:12.020
So one of the things
we've done at the ACLU is

00:58:12.020 --> 00:58:17.020
to recognize that the fight
here is not simply a legal fight

00:58:18.040 --> 00:58:21.210
in the courts, it is a fight of all of us,

00:58:21.210 --> 00:58:25.570
and those 1.75 million people
who have come to join us,

00:58:25.570 --> 00:58:28.640
they don't want, just want that card,

00:58:28.640 --> 00:58:31.650
you know, in the mail, or emailed to them.

00:58:31.650 --> 00:58:35.040
They don't just want to get, you know,

00:58:35.040 --> 00:58:39.700
an inordinate number of email
action alerts in their inbox,

00:58:39.700 --> 00:58:42.000
they actually want to take action.

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:43.750
So one of the things we did was

00:58:43.750 --> 00:58:48.020
to create something called a People Power,

00:58:48.020 --> 00:58:50.450
which has, I think, an
unfortunately sort of

00:58:52.238 --> 00:58:54.590
'60s kind of a name to it,

00:58:54.590 --> 00:58:56.150
it seems a little old-fashioned to me,

00:58:56.150 --> 00:58:59.187
but we created People Power.

00:58:59.187 --> 00:59:04.187
And what People Power is
is a platform to encourage

00:59:04.530 --> 00:59:08.320
and facilitate local activism

00:59:08.320 --> 00:59:10.980
by citizens who care about civil liberties

00:59:10.980 --> 00:59:14.850
and civil rights in a coordinated fashion,

00:59:14.850 --> 00:59:19.660
but a decentralized and
local, through decentralized

00:59:19.660 --> 00:59:21.130
and local action.

00:59:21.130 --> 00:59:25.280
And so the first campaign,
which was launched

00:59:25.280 --> 00:59:28.889
with a video, an hour-long
video presentation done,

00:59:28.889 --> 00:59:33.889
shot live in Miami, Florida,
was about sanctuary cities,

00:59:33.980 --> 00:59:36.110
it was about getting citizens together

00:59:36.110 --> 00:59:38.090
to encourage their towns and cities

00:59:38.090 --> 00:59:40.160
to adopt sanctuary policies.

00:59:40.160 --> 00:59:43.970
And over a million
people watched the video,

00:59:43.970 --> 00:59:47.150
people watched it in house
parties across this country

00:59:47.150 --> 00:59:50.230
in every state, multiple house parties,

00:59:50.230 --> 00:59:54.610
and then we gave them
suggestions for how to go out

00:59:54.610 --> 00:59:58.860
and seek to encourage
their local governments

00:59:58.860 --> 01:00:01.900
to respect the rights of immigrants.

01:00:01.900 --> 01:00:03.503
The same, the same thing,

01:00:05.280 --> 01:00:10.280
the most recent campaign is a
campaign about voting rights,

01:00:10.280 --> 01:00:13.670
let the people vote, and we have, again,

01:00:13.670 --> 01:00:16.070
we launched it through a video,

01:00:16.070 --> 01:00:19.490
a live videotape presentation
that people were invited

01:00:19.490 --> 01:00:24.090
to watch in house parties across
this country, and they did.

01:00:24.090 --> 01:00:27.380
And we have state specific campaigns

01:00:27.380 --> 01:00:31.880
in all 50 states that people can take up

01:00:31.880 --> 01:00:35.340
and act upon, and that's, I think,

01:00:35.340 --> 01:00:38.680
a tremendous, tremendously important part,

01:00:38.680 --> 01:00:43.680
it is grassroots mobilization
in defense of civil liberties.

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:48.270
Why is the NRA so
powerful, it is so powerful

01:00:48.270 --> 01:00:51.650
because it has not 1.75 million members,

01:00:51.650 --> 01:00:56.650
but five million members,
and it has 15 million others

01:00:57.040 --> 01:01:01.340
who think they're members,
but don't pay their dues.

01:01:01.340 --> 01:01:04.410
And when I interview the
NRA officials about this,

01:01:04.410 --> 01:01:06.257
they said, "Well, we'd
love to have their dues,

01:01:06.257 --> 01:01:08.117
"but what we really want is for them

01:01:08.117 --> 01:01:09.647
"to identify as NRA members,

01:01:09.647 --> 01:01:12.427
"because that means we
have 20 million people

01:01:12.427 --> 01:01:15.667
"that we can reach out to to engage

01:01:15.667 --> 01:01:19.077
"when we think gun
rights are under attack."

01:01:19.970 --> 01:01:23.833
And so they have 20
million people, one right.

01:01:24.670 --> 01:01:29.020
We have 1.75 million
people, the whole rest

01:01:29.020 --> 01:01:33.320
of the Bill of Rights, so
we've still got a ways to go,

01:01:33.320 --> 01:01:37.686
but what they have, what they've shown is

01:01:37.686 --> 01:01:41.697
that the strongest support of civil rights

01:01:41.697 --> 01:01:43.763
and civil liberties is not the court,

01:01:45.050 --> 01:01:47.520
but it is the people, and indeed,

01:01:47.520 --> 01:01:50.900
even after the Supreme Court
recognized an individual right

01:01:50.900 --> 01:01:54.800
to bear arms, in the
DC versus Heller case,

01:01:54.800 --> 01:01:57.660
in 2008, it is not the second amendment

01:01:58.650 --> 01:02:01.010
that stops, that protects gun rights,

01:02:01.010 --> 01:02:05.560
and stops gun control
legislation, it is the NRA,

01:02:05.560 --> 01:02:08.710
because the NRA is able to stop laws

01:02:08.710 --> 01:02:11.610
from getting enacted that would
clearly be constitutional,

01:02:13.150 --> 01:02:15.260
and it is able to get laws enacted

01:02:15.260 --> 01:02:19.060
that protect gun rights that
clearly would not be required.

01:02:19.060 --> 01:02:21.470
The court in the Heller
case didn't say you can't

01:02:21.470 --> 01:02:23.340
regulate guns, it said guns are subject

01:02:23.340 --> 01:02:24.510
to reasonable regulation,

01:02:24.510 --> 01:02:26.660
and they gave all kinds of examples.

01:02:26.660 --> 01:02:29.210
So it's the political check of the NRA,

01:02:29.210 --> 01:02:31.460
not the constitutional check of the courts

01:02:31.460 --> 01:02:34.510
that is the ultimate
protector of that right.

01:02:34.510 --> 01:02:38.780
And what may happen now is that the

01:02:38.780 --> 01:02:42.940
high school students may give

01:02:42.940 --> 01:02:46.520
impetus to a similar local,

01:02:46.520 --> 01:02:50.450
you know, a state by state campaign

01:02:50.450 --> 01:02:52.860
to push back against the NRA, something

01:02:52.860 --> 01:02:57.860
that we really haven't
had in this country yet.

01:02:58.110 --> 01:03:02.090
So People Power is one of
the ways that we've responded

01:03:02.090 --> 01:03:04.070
to Trump, another way we've responded is

01:03:04.070 --> 01:03:06.123
through social media,

01:03:08.142 --> 01:03:12.040
and, you know, here, Donald
Trump has shown us the power

01:03:12.040 --> 01:03:12.940
of social media, right?

01:03:12.940 --> 01:03:17.050
He can speak directly
to the American people

01:03:17.050 --> 01:03:19.963
through his Twitter account,
for better or for worse.

01:03:21.470 --> 01:03:23.870
But it's not just Donald
Trump that can do that,

01:03:24.728 --> 01:03:26.650
I, in my second week on the job,

01:03:26.650 --> 01:03:30.150
I sat in on a meeting
of our coms department,

01:03:30.150 --> 01:03:32.790
our communications department,
and it was amazing,

01:03:32.790 --> 01:03:35.220
it was like, it was like
being in a newsroom.

01:03:35.220 --> 01:03:37.107
There were 30 people, and
they'd get up, and say,

01:03:37.107 --> 01:03:39.437
"Well, this is, this is the
video we created this week,

01:03:39.437 --> 01:03:41.507
"and this is the issue that we're pushing,

01:03:41.507 --> 01:03:43.457
"and we got this interview,
and that interview,

01:03:43.457 --> 01:03:47.037
"and this many hits,
and here's what happened

01:03:47.037 --> 01:03:48.217
"on the piece of legislation

01:03:48.217 --> 01:03:51.190
"that was at issue in this state."

01:03:51.190 --> 01:03:55.930
And it was, it was remarkable,
and I said to them,

01:03:55.930 --> 01:03:59.677
you know, "When I started
out as a civil rights lawyer

01:03:59.677 --> 01:04:01.217
"with the Center for
Constitutional Rights,

01:04:01.217 --> 01:04:03.847
"a scrappier, smaller version of the ACLU,

01:04:03.847 --> 01:04:07.007
"back in the 1980s, we
had a coms department,

01:04:07.007 --> 01:04:10.730
"it was one guy, he was the PR guy."

01:04:10.730 --> 01:04:13.550
And what would he do, he
would file a press release

01:04:13.550 --> 01:04:17.640
when we filed a lawsuit, he
would file a press release

01:04:17.640 --> 01:04:20.860
when we had a hearing, he
would file a press release

01:04:20.860 --> 01:04:22.800
when we won a lawsuit,

01:04:22.800 --> 01:04:24.930
and sometimes he'd file
a press release even

01:04:24.930 --> 01:04:27.650
when we lost a lawsuit, right, but,

01:04:27.650 --> 01:04:29.510
and what was he doing
with those press releases?

01:04:29.510 --> 01:04:33.710
Trying to get the media,
especially The New York Times,

01:04:33.710 --> 01:04:37.440
to cover our cases,
well, we still do that,

01:04:37.440 --> 01:04:39.990
