Convention flag burning case,

01:16:08.600 --> 01:16:10.400
along with Joey Johnson,

01:16:10.400 --> 01:16:13.260
from Texas v. Johnson's
a good friend of mine.

01:16:13.260 --> 01:16:14.850
- Yep, my former client.

01:16:14.850 --> 01:16:16.950
- [Man] So I'm very familiar both

01:16:16.950 --> 01:16:20.980
with the authoritarian attacks
that have been happening,

01:16:20.980 --> 01:16:25.330
but also, our cases were
dropped, and all the ways

01:16:25.330 --> 01:16:28.780
in which the courts
have beaten back, and I,

01:16:28.780 --> 01:16:31.100
beaten back these various attacks on lots

01:16:31.100 --> 01:16:33.290
of different fronts,
and I appreciate the way

01:16:33.290 --> 01:16:35.010
that you talked about the combination

01:16:35.010 --> 01:16:37.723
of civil society activism, along with,

01:16:38.750 --> 01:16:41.740
you know, the legal battles in the courts.

01:16:41.740 --> 01:16:45.880
My question is about the actual dynamic

01:16:45.880 --> 01:16:48.220
that's been happening where, yes,

01:16:48.220 --> 01:16:50.260
things have been beaten
back on various fronts,

01:16:50.260 --> 01:16:53.570
but the Trump regime keeps pushing forward

01:16:53.570 --> 01:16:56.638
on many other fronts,
including finding other ways,

01:16:56.638 --> 01:16:58.720
you know, besides just the Muslim ban,

01:16:58.720 --> 01:17:01.020
whether it's extreme
vetting, or whether it's,

01:17:01.870 --> 01:17:04.060
you know, different, other restrictions,

01:17:04.060 --> 01:17:06.190
and ways to keep people
from those countries.

01:17:06.190 --> 01:17:08.860
And on top of that,
there's the question of,

01:17:08.860 --> 01:17:13.370
you know, using incidents
in the same way you talked

01:17:13.370 --> 01:17:14.960
about in the, the Palmer raids,

01:17:14.960 --> 01:17:17.810
they used those terrorist
bombings, there's, I mean,

01:17:17.810 --> 01:17:20.570
look at what Bush used
9/11 to do, can you imagine

01:17:20.570 --> 01:17:24.070
if there's some incident like that now,

01:17:24.070 --> 01:17:26.510
with this guy in the White House?

01:17:26.510 --> 01:17:31.310
So my question is, I guess I agree with

01:17:33.070 --> 01:17:37.020
the, the hope that you have,
but I also think we have

01:17:37.020 --> 01:17:41.320
to confront how dangerous
the situation is,

01:17:41.320 --> 01:17:46.320
and rather than just fighting
against each separate attack

01:17:46.430 --> 01:17:49.660
on people, don't we need
to actually mobilize all

01:17:49.660 --> 01:17:51.430
those people that were in the airports,

01:17:51.430 --> 01:17:52.850
that were at the women's
march, don't we need

01:17:52.850 --> 01:17:57.470
to mobilize them to drive the
regime from power altogether?

01:17:57.470 --> 01:18:02.470
- So, you know, I think,
yeah, there are many,

01:18:02.860 --> 01:18:04.270
there are many attacks,

01:18:04.270 --> 01:18:09.270
the Trump administration
has gone after many targets,

01:18:09.920 --> 01:18:11.630
and so it's a challenge.

01:18:11.630 --> 01:18:13.320
I mean, you know, we have,

01:18:13.320 --> 01:18:15.500
because we're a multi issue organization,

01:18:15.500 --> 01:18:18.780
we're, we've been able to
respond to many of them,

01:18:18.780 --> 01:18:21.090
but there are plenty
that we can't respond to,

01:18:21.090 --> 01:18:23.030
the environment attacks, the, you know,

01:18:23.030 --> 01:18:26.610
the environment groups are responding to.

01:18:26.610 --> 01:18:29.850
There are a whole host of organizations

01:18:29.850 --> 01:18:31.680
that are fighting back in various ways,

01:18:31.680 --> 01:18:34.390
and I think it takes the
work of all of us to do it.

01:18:34.390 --> 01:18:36.900
In terms of, you know, getting
the regime out of power,

01:18:36.900 --> 01:18:41.160
that's what elections are
for, there will be midterms,

01:18:41.160 --> 01:18:45.060
I think, you know, the, I'm optimistic

01:18:45.060 --> 01:18:46.960
about the midterms, about the possibility

01:18:46.960 --> 01:18:48.987
of people who believe in civil rights

01:18:48.987 --> 01:18:52.260
and civil liberties getting elected,

01:18:52.260 --> 01:18:56.090
and that will put a further
constraint on the president.

01:18:56.090 --> 01:19:00.140
I'm optimistic about
2020, when we get there.

01:19:00.140 --> 01:19:03.923
You know, Donald Trump was elected with,

01:19:06.580 --> 01:19:09.870
losing the popular vote, he
got three million fewer votes

01:19:09.870 --> 01:19:11.810
than Hillary Clinton, he won because

01:19:11.810 --> 01:19:14.670
of the peculiarity of
our electoral college.

01:19:14.670 --> 01:19:17.060
He came into office with
the lowest approval rating

01:19:17.060 --> 01:19:18.950
of any president in history,

01:19:18.950 --> 01:19:21.810
and his approval rating
has fallen since then.

01:19:21.810 --> 01:19:22.643
So,

01:19:23.908 --> 01:19:27.680
in a democracy, that is a significant

01:19:28.540 --> 01:19:29.620
hindrance

01:19:29.620 --> 01:19:32.450
to getting done what you want to get done.

01:19:32.450 --> 01:19:34.100
Most of what he's gotten done is

01:19:34.100 --> 01:19:36.810
through unilateral executive action,

01:19:36.810 --> 01:19:39.490
and the thing about
unilateral executive action is

01:19:39.490 --> 01:19:42.140
that there's quite a bit of room

01:19:42.140 --> 01:19:45.160
for unilateral executive
action, but it can be reversed

01:19:45.160 --> 01:19:49.860
by the next president, if we
elect a president who cares

01:19:49.860 --> 01:19:52.500
about civil rights and civil liberties.

01:19:52.500 --> 01:19:56.870
So I think the response is
through the democratic process,

01:19:56.870 --> 01:20:01.210
and, you know, as to the
risk of a terrorist incident,

01:20:01.210 --> 01:20:03.900
absolutely, that's a concern, but look,

01:20:03.900 --> 01:20:07.723
you know, George Bush had more, more,

01:20:08.764 --> 01:20:11.570
more going for him than President Trump.

01:20:11.570 --> 01:20:16.233
He did not, when 9/11 happened,

01:20:17.140 --> 01:20:20.500
he had a Congress on his side,

01:20:20.500 --> 01:20:21.630
he had the court on his side, in fact,

01:20:21.630 --> 01:20:23.650
it was the court that put him into office

01:20:23.650 --> 01:20:26.073
through Bush versus
Gore, it was his court.

01:20:27.882 --> 01:20:30.780
And he had a history of
deference to the president

01:20:30.780 --> 01:20:34.813
in times of crisis, and he
had 90% approval ratings.

01:20:36.370 --> 01:20:39.580
And yet, by the time, and he acted in,

01:20:39.580 --> 01:20:42.650
he over-responded to the attacks on 9/11,

01:20:42.650 --> 01:20:45.170
and authorized torture,
and disappearances,

01:20:45.170 --> 01:20:49.943
and Guantanamo and the like,
but by the time he left office,

01:20:50.870 --> 01:20:54.820
he had released over 500
people from Guantanamo,

01:20:54.820 --> 01:20:59.820
he had closed down the secret
prisons in eastern Europe,

01:20:59.860 --> 01:21:02.400
he had suspended the torture program,

01:21:02.400 --> 01:21:04.540
he had stopped extraordinary rendition,

01:21:04.540 --> 01:21:06.130
where we abducted people, and sent them

01:21:06.130 --> 01:21:07.670
to other countries to be tortured.

01:21:07.670 --> 01:21:11.660
And he did that in
response to civil society

01:21:14.250 --> 01:21:15.530
advocacy

01:21:15.530 --> 01:21:19.920
that made it too costly for
him to continue those efforts,

01:21:19.920 --> 01:21:23.480
in particular, because foreign
countries were unwilling

01:21:23.480 --> 01:21:28.480
to work with him because
he was so tainted by these,

01:21:28.800 --> 01:21:33.800
these acts, so if we could
push back against George Bush,

01:21:33.960 --> 01:21:35.770
who had 90% approval ratings,

01:21:35.770 --> 01:21:38.240
surely we can push back
against Donald Trump,

01:21:38.240 --> 01:21:40.833
who doesn't, can't even
